<section>
    <h2>Objective</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>
            You've been divided into teams.  Work with your team to score points. 
            At the end of the time limit, teams will be ranked according to their cumulative scores.
        </li>
        <li>
            Throughout the competition, you'll be searching for "flags".
        </li>
        <li>
            These flags are worth varying amounts of points.
        </li>
        <li>
            You can submit them on the tournament leaderboard page.
        </li>
        <li>
            A flag will always be a string of text.  These strings will vary in length.
        </li>
        <li>
            Flag strings come in two forms:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    Some puzzles will tell you that a string is a flag. 
                    These strings can look like anything, but they'll usually (but not always) look like hashes. 
                </li>
                <li>
                    Any string you find that starts with "FLAG" in all-caps, followed by an underscore and some text:
                    <span style="font-family: monospace">FLAG_{TEXT}</span>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            BEWARE!
            <ul>
                <li>
                    There are <strong>red herring flags</strong> out there!
                    These are worth <strong>NEGATIVE POINTS</strong>.
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            Red herring flags are typically found as an incorrect solution to a puzzle. 
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Some of them give your team a chance to "spend" some points for a hint. 
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            "<span style="font-family: monospace">FLAG_{TEXT}</span>" flags are always safe.  These ones are like "treasure chests" to encourage exploration.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Here's a test of your comprehension.  Here are two flags.  The second one is worth points, the first one is a red herring. 
                </li>
                <li>
                    Flag 1: <pre>k823bknciwe7w872</pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Flag 2: <pre>lslfi8sern</pre>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            Look everywhere for flags!  They may turn up in unexpected spots.  
            <ul>
                <li>
                    It would be a real shame if nobody found the secrets in this website's source code... <span style="color: transparent">FNORD</span>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
</section>

